Assessment 2: CartoDB IMD Map

201347125

13 May, 2019

Embedded Map

Web Based Map

Also available at https://gdsl.carto.com/u/cillian-envs456-19/builder/3ce9fb67-667f-4b15-8d40-f4a3d7de1331/embed which may be easier to navigate.

Discusson

The dark base map was created using Mapbox, removing some unnecessary labels such as points of interest, and altering the font to my preference. The base layer of the CartoDB map provides an outline of the Liverpool Local Authority District. The Indices of Multiple Deprivation is the primary focus of this map, aggregated into 10 deciles. Included for this layer is a widget which gives an overview of the distribution of IMD deciles within Liverpool (primarily low, indicating higher deprivation), additionally the colour scheme was selected as diverging, due to the large number of bins (10), this allowed for a clearer differentiation between each decile. The code to produce 10 bins in CartoDB is given:

#layer {
  polygon-fill: ramp([deciles], (
#a50026,
#d73027,
#f46d43,
#fdae61,
#fee08b,
#d9ef8b,
#a6d96a,
#66bd63,
#1a9850,
#006837), quantiles);
  polygon-opacity: 0.75;
}
#layer::outline {
  line-width: 1;
  line-color: #000000;
  line-opacity: 0.5;
}

These deciles were included from a source that didnt include geometry, so were combined with the existing LSOA geometry within CartoDB with the code below:

SELECT dec_1.deciles,
e08000012_1.lsoa11cd,
e08000012_1.the_geom_webmercator, 
e08000012_1.cartodb_id
FROM dec_1,
e08000012_1
WHERE dec_1.lsoa11cd = e08000012_1.lsoa11cd

In addition to the IMD Deciles, a Local Indicators of Spatial Association (LISA) analysis was run in CartoDB to indicate clusters of unusually high or low IMD Scores. Using similar colours to IMD Deciles the outline for this layer is white as opposed to black to remove confusion between the layers. Additionally it is advised to observe this layer only with IMD Deciles toggled off.

Crime points have been added and aggregated into hex bins to give an overview of the distribution of crime within Liverpool, by default only the top and bottom 5 LSOAs by number of crimes have been included. The colour of each bin indicates the number of crimes, shown with a number inside each. The widget for this layer allows for the selection of particular types of crime.

Finally Liverpool city centre was included as a point and buffered to 4km, with each kilometer shown by a black band. This gives some insight into how the proximity towards the city centre appears to influence both crime and the level of deprivation. For example, at the very centre crime is high but deprivation appears to be relatively low, outside the very centre of the city crime is high as well as deprivation. Additionally Liverpool shows a clear divide between the north and south, where the south shows both low levels of crime and low deprivation, parallel to the north with high crime and deprivation.

There is an abundance of literature that associates crime and deprivation (e.g.Dorling et al. 2000), where income inequality and social relations encourage the higher levels of crime. Additionally a study within Liverpool found that fear of crime from residents within Liverpools tower blocks is most apparent in the areas highlighted in this map, (Green 2002), this study also showed that it is likely that fear of crime has negative consequences on mental health. One particular highlight I have aimed to detail with this map is the relatively low levels of deprivation towards Liverpools city centre, despite the high levels of crime. It is likely that this may be attributable to the tourist population that regularly visit the city for its nightlife culture, and a detailed look into the types of crime found towards the city centre reflects that of typical crimes related to drinking and drugs offenses (Pizam 1999).

References

Dorling, Danny, Richard Mitchell, Mary Shaw, Scott Orford, and George Davey Smith. 2000. The Ghost of Christmas Past: Health Effects of Poverty in London in 1896 and 1991. Bmj 321 (7276): 154751.

Green, G. 2002. Fear of Crime and Health in Residential Tower Blocks: A Case Study in Liverpool, UK. The European Journal of Public Health 12 (1): 1015. https://doi.org/10.1093/eurpub/12.1.10.

Pizam, Abraham. 1999. A Comprehensive Approach to Classifying Acts of Crime and Violence at Tourism Destinations. Journal of Travel Research 38 (1): 512.
